.TH _printf 3 "2025-08-30" "1.0" "holbertonschool-printf"
.SH NAME
_printf \- produce output according to a format

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a format string, writing to standard output (stdout).  
It is a simplified version of the standard
.B printf
function, supporting a limited set of conversion specifiers.

The
.B format
string is composed of zero or more directives:
ordinary characters (except `%') are printed as is;
conversion specifications beginning with `%'
are replaced by corresponding arguments.

.SH SUPPORTED CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B c
Print a single character.
.TP
.B s
Print a null-terminated string. If a NULL pointer is passed, prints "(null)".
.TP
.B %
Print a literal percent sign.
.TP
.B d, i
Print a signed decimal integer.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful completion,
.B _printf
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the terminating null byte).  
If
.B format
is NULL, the function returns -1.

.SH LIMITATIONS
.PP
This
.B _printf
does not support:
.RS
.IP
flag characters (such as '-', '+', ' ', '#', '0')
.IP
field width
.IP
precision
.IP
length modifiers (such as 'l', 'h')
.RE

Unknown conversion specifiers are printed as-is, including the preceding `%`.

.SH EXAMPLE
.IP
.B #include "main.h"
.IP
.B _printf("Hello %s! You scored %d%% on your test.\n", "Alice", 95);

.SH AUTHOR
Written as part of the holbertonschool-printf project.

